Absolutely; start off with exploratory data analysis to explore your data and develop hypotheses to test, and then use modelling/ML if you want to see if differences you found are statistically significant and/or to make predictions on new data.
For example, comparing which age groups, produce the most spend. That might be best to just explore visually (Histograms) - as opposed to trying to model""

Also, why are you modelling it? Do you want something that you can interpret the predictors from, or do you just want to predict future values? This can influence whether a more black-box" ML approach or more traditional statistical model is a better fit."

Categorical predictors are fine. If you have a factor (predictor) with multiple levels (categories), it treats one as a 'reference' category, and models the other level(s) as compared to it. Also read up on dummy variable encoding as that may be more appropriate. (2/2)

OK, spend sounds like a decent candidate for your model. You'll probably want to plot a histogram of spend and see if it looks approximately normally distributed; QQ-plots can also be used for this. (1/2)
you can use decision trees that incorporate regression https:// machinelearningmastery.com/classification -and-regression-trees-for-machine-learning/ …
Does Linear work well, with categorical predictors? And we're predicting spend
Depends on what exactly it is that you're predicting - what's your target variable? Not overcomplicating things, and starting with a linear model is probably a decent starting point though.
